Self Driving Car Engineer Nanodegree¶

Project: Build a Vehicle Detection Pipeline¶

In this project, the goal is to write a software pipeline to detect vehicles in a video (start with the test_video.mp4 and later implement on full project_video.mp4).

The goals / steps of this project are the following:

  • Perform a Histogram of Oriented Gradients (HOG) feature extraction on a labeled training set of images and train a classifier Linear SVM classifier
  • Optionally, you can also apply a color transform and append binned color features, as well as histograms of color, to your HOG feature vector.
  • Note: for those first two steps don't forget to normalize your features and randomize a selection for training and testing.
  • Implement a sliding-window technique and use your trained classifier to search for vehicles in images.
  • Run your pipeline on a video stream (start with the test_video.mp4 and later implement on full project_video.mp4) and create a heat map of recurring detections frame by frame to reject outliers and follow detected vehicles.
  • Estimate a bounding box for vehicles detected.

Here are links to the labeled data for vehicle and non-vehicle examples to train your classifier. These example images come from a combination of the GTI vehicle image database, the KITTI vision benchmark suite, and examples extracted from the project video itself. You are welcome and encouraged to take advantage of the recently released Udacity labeled dataset to augment your training data.

Step 0: Preparation¶

As a first step some functions are declared which will later be used to read in the data, bring it into a congruent format and feed it into the pipeline.

    with open(path, mode="wb") as f:
        print("Saving data to: {}".format(path))
        pickle.dump(data, f)
        print("Done.")

# LOAD DATA
# Load pickled data
"""
path: path to load data from
return: data that was loaded
"""
def load_data(path):
    with open(path, mode="rb") as f:
        print("Loading data from: {}". format(path))
        data = pickle.load(f)
        print("Done.")
    return data

# PRINT INFORMATION
# Print some information of the dataset
"""
data_frame: pandas DataFrame object that contains the data
name: name of the dataset
"""
def print_dataset_info(data, name="Dataset"):
    classes = np.unique(data["label"])
    percentage_car = data[data["label"] == "car"].shape[0] / data.shape[0] * 100
    print("-"*50)
    print(name)
    print("-"*50)
    print("Number of classes = {}".format(classes.shape[0]))
    print("Number of samples = {}".format(data.shape[0]))
    print("Percentage of car images: {:.2f}%".format(percentage_car))

    # Show distribution of labels in the dataset
    class_list = pd.DataFrame(data={"class": classes})
    class_list["amount"] = [sum(data["label"]==c) for c in classes]
    display(class_list.sort_values("amount", ascending=False))

# FORMAT DATASET
# Brings dataset into desired format for further processing which is 
# a pandas DataFrame with columns: frame, xmax, ymax, xmin, ymin, label
"""
target: single path to a csv file or dict of key=label value=[path]
store_path: path to save or load data 
match_map: dict to map columns of csv files to columns of desired Data Frame key=target_column value=source_column
return: pandas DataFrame of the data with columns: frame, xmax, ymax, xmin, ymin
"""
def format_dataset(target , store_path, match_map=None):
    # Create dict to fill data into
    data = {"frame": [], "xmax": [], "ymax": [], "xmin": [], "ymin": [], "label": []}
    if isinstance(target, dict):
        # Loop over each key value pair in the target dict
        for label, paths in target.items():
            # Loop over each path in the paths list
            for path in paths:
                # Get all image (.png and .jpg) files
                frames = glob.glob(os.path.join(path, "*.png"))
                frames.extend(glob.glob(os.path.join(path, "*.jpg")))
                frames = [os.path.normpath(p) for p in frames]
                # Add data to the dict
                data["frame"].extend(frames)
                data["label"].extend([label]*len(frames))
                data["xmax"].extend([None]*len(frames))
                data["ymax"].extend([None]*len(frames))
                data["xmin"].extend([None]*len(frames))
                data["ymin"].extend([None]*len(frames))

    elif isinstance(target, str):
        # Check whether passed file is .csv
        if os.path.splitext(target)[1] == ".csv":
            # Read in data from csv
            source = pd.read_csv(target)
            # Remap csv columns to desired output
            for column in data:
                match = match_map[column]
                if not match == None:
                    data[column] = source[match]
                else:
                    data[column] = [None]*source.shape[0]
            # Get path to the frames
            data_path = os.path.dirname(target)
            # Add path information to frame
            data["frame"] = [os.path.normpath(os.path.join(data_path, file)) for file in data["frame"]]
        else:
            print("Pass .csv file or dict")

    # Create DataFrame
    data = pd.DataFrame(data=data)
    
    return data

# GET DATA
# Composes data from multiple sources into one
"""
datasets: list that describes which data to get and can be 1: standard, 2: udacity_1, and 3: udacity_2
return: composed dataset
"""
def get_data(data_sets=[1, 2, 3]):
    standard_data_paths = {"non-car": ["non-vehicles/non-vehicles/Extras/", "non-vehicles/non-vehicles/GTI/"], 
                          "car": ["vehicles/vehicles/GTI_Far/", "vehicles/vehicles/GTI_Left/", 
                                      "vehicles/vehicles/GTI_Right/", "vehicles/vehicles/GTI_MiddleClose/",
                                      "vehicles/vehicles/KITTI_extracted/"]}
    # Additional data: Read in dataset 1 from Udacity dataset available at
    # https://github.com/udacity/self-driving-car/tree/master/annotations
    udacity_1_data_path = "object-detection-crowdai/object-detection-crowdai/labels.csv"
    # ROI information has mixed up headers in csv so it is fixed here
    udacity_1_match_map = {"frame": "frame", "xmax": "ymin", "ymax": "ymax", "xmin": "xmin", "ymin": "xmax", "label": "label"}
    # Additional data: Read in dataset 2 from Udacity dataset available at
    # https://github.com/udacity/self-driving-car/tree/master/annotations
    # The labels.csv of this dataset has to be adapted before reading it:
    # * add column headers
    # * change delimiter from " " to ","
    # Otherwise the traffic light labels will lead to problems as the number of columns is inconsistent
    udacity_2_data_path = "object-dataset/object-dataset/labels.csv"
    udacity_2_match_map = {"frame": "frame", "xmax": "xmax", "ymax": "ymax", "xmin": "xmin", "ymin": "ymin", "label": "label"}
    # Dict to handle dataset mappings and their store paths
    data_sources = {1: [standard_data_paths, "standard_data.p"], 
                    2: [udacity_1_data_path, "udacity_1_data.p", udacity_1_match_map],
                    3: [udacity_2_data_path, "udacity_2_data.p", udacity_2_match_map]}
    data = pd.DataFrame()
    # Read in data
    data = data.append([format_dataset(*data_sources[key]) for key in data_sets])
    # Make all labels lowercase
    data["label"] = data["label"].str.lower()
    
    return data

# MAP LABELS
# Map existing labels to desired labels
"""
data: dataset
mapping: list of tuples (target_label, list_of_labels_to_convert) to change labels 
return: dataset with rearranged labels
"""
def map_labels(data, mapping):
    # Loop through the mapping items
    for target, labels in mapping:
        if not labels == None: 
            # Loop through the labels that should be converted
            for label in labels:
                # Change current label to desired one
                data["label"][data["label"] == label] = target
        # If labels == None map every remaining label to target
        else: 
            # Get list of all used targets and remove the current target
            used_targets = list(np.array(mapping)[:,0])
            used_targets.remove(target)
            # Change all labels that were not mapped yet
            indices = [all(hit_list) for hit_list in zip(*[data["label"] != used_target for used_target in used_targets])]
            data["label"][indices] = target
    return data

# READ IMAGE
# Reads in a single image and converts it to RGB
# TODO: Maybe extract cropping and resizing into extra functions to be able to pipeline them
"""
sample: a signle row of DataFrame
crop: decides whether to crop the image's ROI or not
image_size: size to resize image to
return: image 
"""
def read_single_image(sample, crop=False, img_size=None):
    # Read in image and convert to RGB
    img = cv2.cvtColor(cv2.imread(sample["frame"]), cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    # Check whether image has to be cropped
    if crop:
        xmin = 0 if sample["xmin"] == None else sample["xmin"]
        ymin = 0 if sample["ymin"] == None else sample["ymin"]
        xmax = img.shape[1] if sample["xmax"] == None else sample["xmax"]
        ymax = img.shape[0] if sample["ymax"] == None else sample["ymax"]
        # Sanity check whether xmin and ymin are actually smaller than xmax and ymax
        if xmin > xmax:
            xmin, xmax = xmax, xmin
        if ymin > ymax:
            ymin, ymax = ymax, ymin
        img = img[ymin:ymax, xmin:xmax]
    # Resize image to desired size
    if not img_size == None:
        img = cv2.resize(img, img_size, interpolation=cv2.INTER_NEAREST)
        
    return img

# READ IMAGES
# Reads in images from DataFrame and converts them to RGB
"""
data_frame: pandas DataFrame that contains the data
crop: boolean whether image should be cropped or not
img_size: resize the image to this dimensions if not None
return: numpy array of the images
"""
def read_images(data_frame, crop=False, img_size=None):
    images = []
    # Loop over the data_frame
    for i, sample in data_frame.iterrows():
        # Read in image, crop it and resize it
        img = read_single_image(sample, crop=crop, img_size=img_size)
        # Add image to list    
        images.append(img)
    # Convert lists to numpy arrays
    X = np.array(images)
    
    return X

# GET BINARIZED LABELS
# Binarizes the labels
"""
data_frame: pandas DataFrame of data to get binarized labels for
label_binarizer: binarizer to use for label binarization
return: numpy array of binarized labels
"""
def get_bin_labels(data_frame, label_binarizer):
    # Binarize labels
    labels = np.array(label_binarizer.transform(data_frame["label"]))
    return labels

# GENERATOR
# Generator to read image data in batches and operate memory efficient
"""
data: the whole dataset DataFrame
label_binarizer: binarizer to use for label binarization
batch_size: number of images to load into memory at once
img_size: size to resize images to
yield: shuffled batch of data
"""
def generator(data, label_binarizer, batch_size=128, img_size=(64,64)):
    num_samples = data.shape[0]
    # Shuffle the data
    shuffle(data)
    # Loop over the whole dataset with stepsize of batch
    for offset in range(0, num_samples, batch_size):
        batch_samples = data[offset:offset+batch_size]
        # Binarize labels of the batch
        y = get_bin_labels(batch_samples, label_binarizer)
        # Get images of the batch
        X = read_images(batch_samples, crop=True, img_size=img_size)

        yield shuffle(X, y)
            
# EPOCH GENERATOR
# Generator to read image data in batches and operate memory efficient
"""
data: the whole dataset DataFrame
label_binarizer: binarizer to use for label binarization
epochs: determines how many epochs to serve the data
batch_size: number of images to load into memory at once
img_size: size to resize images to
yield: shuffled batch of data
"""
def epoch_generator(data, label_binarizer, epochs=5, batch_size=128, img_size=(64,64)):
    num_samples = data.shape[0]
    # Loop forever so the generator never terminates
    # Shuffle the data
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        shuffle(data)
        # Loop over the whole dataset with stepsize of batch
        for offset in range(0, num_samples, batch_size):
            batch_samples = data[offset:offset+batch_size]
            # Binarize labels of the batch
            y = get_bin_labels(batch_samples, label_binarizer)
            # Get images of the batch
            X = read_images(batch_samples, crop=True, img_size=img_size)
            
            yield shuffle(X, y)
            
# PLOT IMAGES            
# Plot images in a grid
"""
data: pandas DataFrame containing the data
crop: determines whether ROI should be cropped of the image
img_size: determines whether to resize images to size
labels: labels of the images that are shown
"""
def plot_images(data, crop=False, img_size=None):
    # Create figure
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    num_examples = data.shape[0]
    # Calculate columns to have close to square dimensions
    columns = np.int(np.sqrt(num_examples))
    rows = np.int(np.ceil(num_examples/columns))
    # Get images of dataset
    imgs = read_images(data, crop=crop, img_size=img_size)
    print("Images shape: {}".format(imgs.shape))
    for key, img in enumerate(imgs):
        plt.subplot(rows, columns, key+1)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.gca().set_title("{}".format(data["label"].iloc[key]), fontsize=10)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
# BOUNDING BOXES
# Draw bounding boxes on an image
"""
img: image to draw on
bboxes: list of tuples with coordinates for top left and bottom right corner
color: color of the bounding boxes as RGB tuple
thick: thickness of the line of the bounding boxes
return: copy of the image with drawn bounding boxes
"""
def draw_boxes(img, bboxes, color=(255, 0, 0), thick=6):
    imcopy = np.copy(img)
    
    for bbox in bboxes:
        cv2.rectangle(imcopy, bbox[0], bbox[1], color, thick)
    return imcopy

# DRAW ROIS
# Draw all regions of interest for a single image
"""
data: the whole dataset
index: index of the image to show ROIs for
"""
def draw_rois(data, index):
    # Get the target sample
    target = data.iloc[index]
    # Find all ROIs belonging to that sample
    rois = data[data["frame"]==target["frame"]]
    # Get bounding boxes
    bboxes = [[(xmin, ymin), (xmax, ymax)] for xmax, xmin, ymax, ymin in rois[["xmax", "xmin", "ymax", "ymin"]].values]
    # Read in the image
    x = read_single_image(target)
    # Show the image with bounding boxes
    plt.imshow(draw_boxes(x, bboxes))

# PLOT COLOR SPACE IN 3D
# Compute 3D scatter plot to visualize image pixels in color space
"""
img: the image which is to analyze 
colors_rgb: colors for the pixel values
axis_labels: list of label names for the axes
axis_limits: tuple with lower and upper limits of the axes
return: Axes3D object
"""
def plot3d(img, colors_rgb, axis_labels=list("RGB"), axis_limits=((0,255), (0,255), (0,255))):
    # Create figure and 3D axes
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    ax = Axes3D(fig)
    
    # Set axis limits
    ax.set_xlim(*axis_limits[0])
    ax.set_ylim(*axis_limits[1])
    ax.set_zlim(*axis_limits[2])
    
    # Set axis labels and sizes
    ax.tick_params(axis="both", which="major", labelsize=14, pad=8)
    ax.set_xlabel(axis_labels[0], fontsize=16, labelpad=16)
    ax.set_ylabel(axis_labels[1], fontsize=16, labelpad=16)
    ax.set_zlabel(axis_labels[2], fontsize=16, labelpad=16)
    
    # Plot pixel values with colors given in colors_rgb
    ax.scatter(
        img[:,:,0].ravel(),
        img[:,:,1].ravel(),
        img[:,:,2].ravel(),
        c=colors_rgb.reshape((-1,3)), edgecolors='none')
    
    return ax

###################################################################
# FEATURE EXTRACTION FUNCTIONS

# Dictionary for color transform mapping on default RGB images
RGB_COLOR_TRANSFORMS = {"HSV": cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV, "HLS": cv2.COLOR_RGB2HLS, "XYZ": cv2.COLOR_RGB2XYZ,
                       "LUV": cv2.COLOR_RGB2LUV, "YUV": cv2.COLOR_RGB2YUV, "YCrCb": cv2.COLOR_RGB2YCrCb,
                       "GRAY": cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY, }
# BGR_COLOR_TRANSFORMS = {"RGB": cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB, "HSV": cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV, "HLS": cv2.COLOR_BGR2HLS,
#                        "LUV": cv2.BGR2LUV, "YUV": cv2.BGR2YUV, "YCrCb": cv2.COLOR_BGR2YCrCb}

# COLOR HISTOGRAM
# Compute color histogram features
"""
img: image to compute the color histogram on
nbins: number of bins for the histogram
bins_range: a tuple with the lower and upper range of the bins
return: histogram for each channel of the image, array with centers of the 
        bins and feature vector of the histograms
"""
def color_hist(img, nbins=32, bins_range=(0, 256)):
    channel_histograms = []
    # Compute the histogram of each channel separately
    red_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,0], bins=nbins, range=bins_range)
    green_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,1], bins=nbins, range=bins_range)
    blue_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,2], bins=nbins, range=bins_range)
    
    # Generating bin centers
    bin_edges = red_hist[1]
    bin_centers = (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[0:len(bin_edges)-1])/2
    
    # Concatenate the histograms into a single feature vector
    histogram_features = np.concatenate((red_hist[0], green_hist[0], blue_hist[0]))
    
    return red_hist, green_hist, blue_hist, bin_centers, histogram_features

# COLOR HISTOGRAM FEATURES
# Get the feature vector from color histograms
"""
img: image to compute the color histogram feature vector on
nbins: number of bins for the histogram
bins_range: a tuple with the lower and upper range of the bins
return: feature vector of color channel histograms
"""
def color_hist_features(img, nbins=32, bins_range=(0, 256)):
    # Compute color histograms
    histograms = color_hist(img, nbins=nbins, bins_range=bins_range)
    
    return histograms[-1]

# SPATIAL BINNING
# Compute spatial color features
"""
img: image that should be converted into spatial features
size: size of spatial feature area
return: spatial feature vector
"""
def bin_spatial(img, size=(32,32)):
    # Create spatial color feature vector
    features = cv2.resize(img, size).ravel()
    
    return features
    
# HOG FEATURES
# Compute histogram of oriented gradients (hog) features
"""
img: image where features should be extracted
orient: number of different gradient orientations to consider
pix_per_cell: size of the cells
cell_per_block: number of cells for each block
vis: should the hog feature visualization be returned
feature_vec: features should be returned as vector
return: features or features and an image with a hog feature visualization
"""
def get_hog_features(img, orient=9, pix_per_cell=8, cell_per_block=2, vis=False, feature_vec=True):
    if vis == True:
        features, hog_image = hog(img, orientations=orient, pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell),
                                 cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), visualise=True, 
                                 feature_vector=feature_vec)
        return features, hog_image
    else:
        features = hog(img, orientations=orient, pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell),
                      cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), visualise=False, feature_vector=feature_vec)
        return features    

# HOG FEATURES
# Get hog features of an image
"""
img: image where features should be extracted
hog_channel: determines which channel to use for hog features can be "ALL", 1, 2,3, or "GRAY"
orient: number of different gradient orientations to consider
pix_per_cell: size of the cells
cell_per_block: number of cells for each block
return: hog features
"""
def hog_features(img, hog_channel="ALL", orient=9, pix_per_cell=8, cell_per_block=2, feature_vec=True):
    if hog_channel == "ALL":
        hog_features = []
        for channel in range(img.shape[2]):
            hog_features.extend(get_hog_features(img[:,:,channel], orient=orient, pix_per_cell=pix_per_cell,
                                                cell_per_block=cell_per_block, vis=False, feature_vec=feature_vec))
        hog_features = np.array(hog_features)
    elif hog_channel == "GRAY":
        feature_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
        hog_features = get_hog_features(img, orient=orient, pix_per_cell=pix_per_cell,cell_per_block=cell_per_block,
                                        vis=False, feature_vec=feature_vec)
    else:
        hog_features = get_hog_features(img[:,:,hog_channel], orient=orient, pix_per_cell=pix_per_cell,
                                        cell_per_block=cell_per_block, vis=False, feature_vec=feature_vec)
    return hog_features 

# COLOR TRANSFORM
# Transforms an image to a target colorspace
"""
img: image to transform
cspace: string of target colorspace
color_transforms: dictionary of transform mapping
return: transformed image
"""
def transform_color(img, cspace=None, color_transforms=RGB_COLOR_TRANSFORMS):
    if cspace != None:
        target_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, color_transforms[cspace])
    else:
        target_img = img
    return target_img

# COMBINE FEATURES
# Extract features from a list of images 
"""
img: list of images to extract features on
pipeline: list of functions that takes in an image and returns a feature vector
color_transformer: transforms the image to desired color space
return: numpy array of feature vector
"""
def extract_img_features(img, pipeline, color_transformer):
    # Transform color space of image
    feature_img = color_transformer(img)
    
    features = np.empty(0)
    if pipeline:
        # Loop through every function in the pipeline
        for func in pipeline:
            # Add new features to feature vector
            features = np.concatenate((features, func(feature_img)), axis=0)

    return features

# EXTRACT FEATURES OF LIST OF IMAGES
# Get features for a list of images
def extract_features(imgs, pipeline, color_transformer):
    # Create a list to append feature vectors to
    features = []
    # Loop over list of images
    for img in imgs:
        sample_features = extract_img_features(img, pipeline, color_transformer)
        # Append the feature vector to the list
        features.append(sample_features)
    features = np.array(features)
    
    return features

            X = extract_features(imgs, pipeline, color_transformer)
            # Concatenate current batch to previous ones 
            features.extend(X)
            labels.extend(y)
        
        # Save data
        save_data((features, labels), file)
    else:
        # Load data
        features, labels = load_data(file)
    
    features = np.array(features)
    labels = np.array(labels)
    return features, labels

parameters: dictionary of parameters for grid search

"""
def train_classifier(X_train, y_train, model, parameters):
    # Creates the grid of possible parameter combinations
    clf = GridSearchCV(model, parameters)
    # Tries all parameter combinations and returns the fitted classifier
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    return clf, clf.best_params_

###################################################################
# OBJECT DETECTION
###################################################################

# SLIDING WINDOW
# Get list of sliding windows
"""
img:
x_start_stop:
y_start_stop:
xy_window:
xy_overlap:
return
"""
def slide_window(img, x_start_stop=[None, None], y_start_stop=[None, None], 
                    xy_window=(64, 64), xy_overlap=(0.5, 0.5)):
    # If x and/or y start/stop positions not defined, set to image size
    if x_start_stop[0] == None:
        x_start_stop[0] = 0
    if x_start_stop[1] == None:
        x_start_stop[1] = img.shape[1]
    if y_start_stop[0] == None:
        y_start_stop[0] = 0
    if y_start_stop[1] == None:
        y_start_stop[1] = img.shape[0]
    # Compute the span of the region to be searched 
    x_span = np.int(x_start_stop[1] - x_start_stop[0])
    y_span = np.int(y_start_stop[1] - y_start_stop[0])
    # Compute the number of pixels per step in x/y
    step_pix_x = xy_window[0]*(1-xy_overlap[0])
    step_pix_y = xy_window[1]*(1-xy_overlap[1])
    # Compute the number of windows in x/y
    x_buffer = np.int(xy_window[0]*xy_overlap[0])
    y_buffer = np.int(xy_window[1]*xy_overlap[1])
    n_windows_x = np.int((x_span-x_buffer)/step_pix_x) 
    n_windows_y = np.int((y_span-y_buffer)/step_pix_y)
    # Initialize a list to append window positions to
    window_list = []
    # Loop through finding x and y window positions
    #     Note: you could vectorize this step, but in practice
    #     you'll be considering windows one by one with your
    #     classifier, so looping makes sense
    for step_y in range(n_windows_y):
        for step_x in range(n_windows_x):
        # Calculate each window position
            start_x = np.int(step_x * step_pix_x + x_start_stop[0])
            start_y = np.int(step_y * step_pix_y + y_start_stop[0])
            end_x = np.int(start_x + xy_window[0])
            end_y = np.int(start_y + xy_window[1])
        # Append window position to list
            window_list.append(((start_x, start_y), (end_x, end_y)))
    # Return the list of windows
    return window_list

# HOG SUBSAMPLING WINDOW SEARCH
# Extract features using hog sub-sampling and make predictions
"""
img:
y_start_stop:
x_start_stop:
scale:
model:
normalizer:
color_transformer:
class_id:
hog_feat:
spatial:
hist:
cells_per_step: instead of overlap define how many cells to step
window:
color: color of the bounding box lines
thick: thickness of the bounding box lines
return:
"""
def find_cars(img, y_start_stop, x_start_stop, scale, model, normalizer, color_transformer, class_id, hog_feat, 
               spatial, hist, cells_per_step=2, window=64, color=(255, 0, 0), thick=6):
    # Copy image to draw on
    draw_img = np.copy(img)
    
    # Set start stop positions if not defined
    if x_start_stop[0] == None:
        x_start_stop[0] = 0
    if x_start_stop[1] == None:
        x_start_stop[1] = img.shape[1]
    if y_start_stop[0] == None:
        y_start_stop[0] = 0
    if y_start_stop[1] == None:
        y_start_stop[1] = img.shape[0]
    
    # Crop image to area of interest
    img_search = img[y_start_stop[0]:y_start_stop[1], x_start_stop[0]:x_start_stop[1], :]
    
    # Tranform to desired color space
    feature_img = color_transformer(img_search)
        
    if scale != 1:
        img_shape = feature_img.shape
        feature_img = cv2.resize(feature_img, (np.int(img_shape[1]/scale), np.int(img_shape[0]/scale)))
    
    img_shape = feature_img.shape
    
    # Define blocks number of blocks and steps
    n_blocks_x = (img_shape[1] // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1 
    n_blocks_y = (img_shape[0] // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1
    n_feat_per_block = orient * np.square(cell_per_block)
    # Calculate blocks per window to be able to crop the features later
    n_blocks_per_window = (window // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1
    n_steps_x = (n_blocks_x - n_blocks_per_window) // cells_per_step
    n_steps_y = (n_blocks_y - n_blocks_per_window) // cells_per_step

    # Compute individual channel hog features
    hog1 = hog_feat(feature_img, 0, vec=False)
    hog2 = hog_feat(feature_img, 1, vec=False)
    hog3 = hog_feat(feature_img, 2, vec=False)
    
    windows = []
    for step_x in range(n_steps_x):
        for step_y in range(n_steps_y):
            pos_y = step_y * cells_per_step
            pos_x = step_x * cells_per_step
            
            # Extract hog for this patch
            # With feature_vec = False the results are stored blockwise in an array
            hog_feat1 = hog1[pos_y:pos_y + n_blocks_per_window, pos_x:pos_x + n_blocks_per_window].ravel() 
            hog_feat2 = hog2[pos_y:pos_y + n_blocks_per_window, pos_x:pos_x + n_blocks_per_window].ravel()
            hog_feat3 = hog3[pos_y:pos_y + n_blocks_per_window, pos_x:pos_x + n_blocks_per_window].ravel()

            hog_features = np.hstack((hog_feat1, hog_feat2, hog_feat3))
            
            # Get start position in pixel values to crop the window out of the image
            x_left = pos_x * pix_per_cell
            y_top = pos_y * pix_per_cell
            
            # Extract the image patch
            sub_img = cv2.resize(feature_img[y_top:y_top+window, x_left:x_left+window], (64,64))
            
            # Get color features
            spatial_features = spatial(sub_img)
            hist_features = hist(sub_img)
            
            # Scale features and make a prediction
            features = normalizer.transform(np.hstack((spatial_features, hist_features, hog_features)).reshape(1, -1))
            prediction = model.predict(features)
            
            # If prediction was car (1)
            if prediction[0] == class_id:
                box_left = np.int(x_left * scale)
                box_top = np.int(y_top * scale)
                win_draw = np.int(window * scale)
                windows.append([(box_left + x_start_stop[0], y_top + y_start_stop[0]), 
                              (box_left + win_draw + x_start_stop[0], y_top + win_draw + y_start_stop[0])])
            
    return windows

# HEATMAP
# Add heat values to heatmap for pixels within bounding box
"""
heatmap: image with pixel values representing heat
bbox_list: list of bounding box coordinates as tuples
return: heatmap with updated heat values
"""
def add_heat(heatmap, bbox_list):
    # Iterate through list of bounding boxes
    for box in bbox_list:
        # Add 1 for all pixels inside each box
        # Assuming each box takes the form ((x1, y1), (x2, y2))
        heatmap[box[0][1]:box[1][1], box[0][0]:box[1][0]] += 1
        
    return heatmap

# Zero values below threshold
"""
heatmap: image with pixel values representing heat
threshold: threshold value for zeroing values
return: thresholded heatmap
"""
def apply_threshold(heatmap, threshold):
    # Zero out pixels below the threshold
    heatmap[heatmap <= threshold] = 0
    
    return heatmap

# Draw bounding boxes around identified objects
"""
img: image to draw on
labels: 
color: color of the bounding boxes
thick: line thickness of the bounding boxes
return: image with bounding boxes
"""
def draw_labeled_bboxes(img, labels, color=(255, 0, 0), thick=6):
    # Iterate through all detected cars
    bboxes = []
    for car_number in range(1, labels[1] + 1):
        # Find pixels with each car_number label value
        nonzero = (labels[0] == car_number).nonzero()
        # Identify x and y values of those pixels
        nonzero_y = np.array(nonzero[0])
        nonzero_x = np.array(nonzero[1])
        # Define a bounding box based on min/max x and y
        bbox = [(np.min(nonzero_x), np.min(nonzero_y)), (np.max(nonzero_x), np.max(nonzero_y))]
        bboxes.append(bbox)
        # Draw box on the image
        cv2.rectangle(img, bbox[0], bbox[1], color, thick)
    
    return img, bboxes

heat_history = []
def video_pipeline(img, model, normalizer, color_transformer, car_id, hog, spatial, hist):
    global heat_history
    # Different scales with start and stop positions
    scales = [(0.75, [400,500], [600,None]), (1, [380,530], [100,1180]), (2, [400,660], [None,None]), (2.5, [350,None], [None,None])]
    windows = []
    for scale in scales:
        window = find_cars(img, scale[1], scale[2], scale[0], model, normalizer, color_transformer, car_id,
                  hog, spatial, hist, cells_per_step=2)
        if window:
            windows.extend(window)
    # Heat map
    heat = np.zeros_like(img[:,:,0]).astype(np.float)
    heat = add_heat(heat, windows)
    heatmap = np.clip(heat, 0, 255)
    heat_history.append(heatmap)
    if len(heat_history) >= 5:
        heat_history.pop(0)
    heatmap = np.sum(np.array(heat_history), axis=0)
    heatmap = apply_threshold(heatmap,15)
    # Find final boxes from heatmap using label function
    labels = label(heatmap)
    if not labels[1] == 0:
        overlay = np.zeros((*heatmap.shape, 3), 'uint8')
        overlay[:,:,0] = np.clip(heatmap*3, 0, 255)
        draw_img = weighted_img(overlay, img, =0.8, =1., =0.)
        draw_img, bboxes = draw_labeled_bboxes(draw_img, labels, color=(0,0,255))
    else:
        draw_img = img
    return draw_img
